caption: Waiter gave excellent service.  Very knowledgeable about menu.  Pasta was good and the appetizer.  The eye rib needed it a little more salt.  Ambience very classy and crowded.  Better reserve or you will wait half an hour..

Fantastic meal, service and wine list!!! On a family vacation here in Miami and we had a very rough start, this restaurant turned everything around for us. The server was attentive and knowledgeable and friendly without being too stuffy. At 9pm, the place was packed with diners that looked like they were having a great time. The bartender was busy but hustling hard and made us a fantastic round of drinks. Our food was delicious, the wine was exceptional and the ambiance looked like a place in a movie. Tempted to dine here two nights in a row!! I never write reviews but this place deserved it. My wife and I are in the restaurant business and really appreciate a great night out for a change.

My wife and I went for the second time. The whole restaurant was screwed up from the first moment of seating to the food. My wife’s chicken was served oozing blood and had no meat on it. My Brussels sprouts must have been cooked by a five year old on the grill not a cook. Her pasta was served incorrectly and when it came it was apparent someone had mistakenly dumped double or triple the salt in by mistake - inedible. For this privilege we were presented a bill of 100. I shared all of this with our server who revealed that neither the owner of the head chef were there that night - in fact it was apparent that they were completely overwhelmed with the staff showing the obvious tension. So there it is - easy as that - one cannot possibly run a restaurant well - and create continuous quality - unless a senior person is on site and is tasting and checking everything. In My hometown of Chicago the food standard and competition drives much much higher performance. We dine out a lot - poor quality has been a constant theme in the Miami - and I’m going to provide very sharp commentary everytime I see it in this City as I eat my way through it.  AVOID TIMO.

Amazing unique food – just found this gem recently while living in Hallandale. Food is obviously creative/unique gourmet and though this is an upscale/$$$ restaurant, they definitely please with portion and flavor! For example, the lamb meatballs with goat cheese came with 5 meatballs and 4 potato/cheese delicious dumplings. I expected smaller portions just because of the restaurant type, but everything exceeded my expectation. They also bring you excellent bread and breadsticks to the table. The truffle carpaccio pizza with cheesy potato puree instead of sauce, is unique and AMAZING – you will crave it a few days later and return for it! Service was excellent from the welcoming host to the prompt and friendly waiter. It's easy to see why this gem has been here for over ten years! We were so full after the meatballs and half of the gourmet-size pizza, that we ended up bringing our whole duck dish home! DELICIOUS! Romantic for date-night also.

Miami Spice Review:  WHAT I TRIED: Maine Lobster Risotto with Summer Corn Soup-  great Pan Roasted Wild Striped Bass- great Butternut Squash Lasagna- good Dark Cherry Pate and Valrhona Chocolate Cremeux- good Crispy Warm Coconut Cake with Creamsicle Frozen Mango- exceptional  HIT: I was going to choose the Maine Lobster Raviolo, until I took one bite of the Coconut Cake. Wow. I honestly did not anything would compare to KYU's Coconut Cake, but Timó's does. The main difference is that KYU's is icing heavy, while the one here highlights the fresh mango. Both are knee-weakeners. I'd like to see them add that to the regular menu.  MISS: Nothing. This is a winning Miami Spice menu.  Vegetarians rejoice! I'd like to also point out that Timó has a separate lovely Vegetable Menu from which I ordered the Butternut Squash Lasagna. Technically speaking, I was not supposed to jump between menus, but I asked nicely.
